            <creation>This story, with the short title "The Unpaid Debt for Cured Blindness," is old: the earliest PEMM manuscript* in which this story appears is from around <date>1700</date>.Originally composed in <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName></creation>
            <abstract>
                <p>A non-Christian man from Wandige had a daughter who was blind. He went to the church of Mary, and he asked her to correct his daughter’s blindness. In exchange, he promised to give her one cow from his daughter’s dowry. Mary granted his wish. Later, when his daughter married, the man offered the cow to her new husband, and his daughter’s blindness returned. Perturbed, the man returned to the church. He prayed for Mary’s forgiveness, and his daughter’s eyesight returned once more. There was a second father, whose daughter also suffered from blindness. When he heard of the miracle granted to the first father, he made the same oath to Mary. He pledged a cow from his daughter’s dowry, and in exchange Mary granted her eyesight. Like the first father, the second betrayed his pledge by giving the cow to his daughter’s husband. When her blindness returned, the second father begged Mary’s pardon. However, she refused to forgive him.</p>
            </abstract>
